27:01.572 --> 27:26.342
Gibbons Creek, that's going to be burning 
lignite, they're going to be puffing all kinds of

27:01.572 --> 27:26.342
radioactivity up that stack of natural 
radioactivity that's been dug out of the earth,

27:01.572 --> 27:26.342
but it's going to be discharged in such a way that it 
comes out of their concentration because there's

27:01.572 --> 27:26.342
uranium in that dirt, in that coal. And that 
uranium is going to go up that stack. So they're

27:31.828 --> 27:40.559
going to have far more environmental impact than 
we would at this facility. Because the byproduct

27:40.579 --> 27:48.269
we have that goes up our stack around research 
reactors, it's a gas. It's contained in air. It's

27:49.651 --> 27:51.113
argon that's in air. And we produce a radioactive 
material any time air gets around the reactor.

27:57.743 --> 27:58.784
because there's argon in there. But the argon has a 
very short half-life. It doesn't stay around very

28:01.467 --> 28:02.628
long. In fact, in a matter of something like five 
hours, it's roughly 90% gone. And we discharge it

28:09.416 --> 28:13.861
at a high altitude. It disperses at a very, very low 
level. In fact, it's so low once it leaves our

28:17.425 --> 28:23.171
facility that we can't even detect it. We must 
detect it inside the facility when it's

28:25.250 --> 28:32.680
concentrated for us to even know that we're 
releasing it. It's that low. There's not a threat

